        "heading": "The Physics of the Color Wheel",
        "body": "To use this strategy, you must first understand the traditional color wheel. Complementary colors are colors that sit at the absolute exact opposite ends of the color wheel. The primary pairs are: • Blue and Orange (The most common cinematic contrast) • Red and Green • Yellow and Purple The Optical Effect: When the human eye sees extreme opposites placed next to each other, a phenomenon known as Simultaneous Contrast occurs. The two colors stimulate entirely different photoreceptors in your eyes. This creates intense visual friction. The colors push against each other, making both colors appear significantly brighter and more vibrant than if they were standing alone."
